PT2M52S 620 349 Autoplay On Off Video feedback Video settings Economists scramble to revise Australian dollar projections Malcolm Maiden: China has made the $A stronger over the long haul The Australian dollar has slumped to a fresh six-year low after the US greenback rose overnight on the back of US labour data which bolstered bets the Fed will cut interest rates at its September meeting.
At 0700 AEST on Saturday, the dollar is trading at 69.08 US cents, its lowest level since April 2009.
The Australian dollar is fetching just above 69 US cents, its lowest mark since April, 2009. Photo: Dominic Lorrimer
It's the latest blow to the dollar, which hit multiple six-year lows this week on concerns over the health of China's economy – Australia's largest export market – and signs that Australia's economy was weaker than expected.
Advertisement Australia's dollar has now fallen nearly 40 per cent against the US dollar since its 2011 high.
The slump has economists predicting more sharp falls for the currency, with some even speculating it could fall as low as US50c in coming years .
"It's the same reason as what we've seen recently," Commonwealth Bank chief currency strategist Richard Grace said.
"Lower commodities prices, speculation of slower global growth led by China, lower Australian bond yields, narrowing interest rate differentials, a weaker Asian stock market - all of those factors have contributed."
Overnight, The US dollar climbed versus most of its 16 major peers as government statistics showed wages grew faster than forecast while the unemployment rate declined. The Fed is scrutinising data for signs of inflation and job creation as it looks to raise its target from virtually zero.
Average hourly earnings advanced 0.3 per cent in August, the most since March, while the jobless rate dropped to 5.1 per cent, the lowest since April 2008 and a level that the Federal Reserve considers to be full employment.
Fed policy makers meeting in less than two weeks will weigh resilient US employment conditions against the recent turmoil in world financial markets as they debate the timing of any interest-rate increase.
